# Changelog (engine/v1/)

## Whole-model floor grounding (`builder/NewEntity.js`)

**What:** `buildModel` now seats an entity's whole-model collision-AABB floor on the surface plane instead of only the root part's bottom face. After the initial `applyModelPose`, a finalization step captures `groundPlaneY = model.rootTransform.position.y` (pre-correction; already folds in the surface origin), computes `computeEntityAabb(model)`, translates `model.rootTransform.position.y` by `groundPlaneY - aabb.min.y`, and re-poses so the `defaultPose` snapshot captures the grounded pose. The per-root half-height grounding is kept as the assembly baseline, so entities whose root is already the lowest part get `delta = 0` (byte-identical output).

**Why:** Grounding by the root part's bottom face let any part hanging below the root (player/character legs, toes, tentacles) clip through the floor; consumers had been hand-tuning vertical offsets to compensate (e.g. Simulator `ent_carl.model.rootTransform.position.y: 0.18`, character root `localPosition.y`). Seating the true AABB floor makes grounding correct for multi-part models regardless of which part is lowest, so `rootTransform.position.y` now means "floor height above the surface." The doubled `computeEntityAabb` (once pre-correction here, once post-reposition in `BuildEntity`) is minimal-necessary: moving entities are repositioned by the movement lerp after `buildModel` returns, so a second scan is unavoidable and the pre-correction scan is a hard prerequisite (DRYAD-confirmed).

**Where:** [builder/NewEntity.js](engine/v1/builder/NewEntity.js) `buildModel`. App-side follow-on (not engine): `carlGames/simulator/entities.json` `ent_carl` `rootTransform.position.y` `0.18 → 0` (the manual lift is now redundant and would otherwise float the model).

## Boot-time engine template instancing (`builder/templates/Instance.js`)

**What:** Moved canonicalization of engine-owned template JSON (player characters, scatter, terrain/obstacle blueprints) from two import-time IIFEs to a single boot-time step. New module [Instance.js](engine/v1/builder/templates/Instance.js) exports `InstanceEngineTemplates()`, which `structuredClone`s the four template singletons into a `raw` object *before* instancing, then calls three private sister functions (`instanceCharacterTemplates` / `instanceScatterTemplates` / `instanceBlueprintTemplates`, sharing a `canonicalizePartTransform` helper) to instance the singletons in place, returning `{ raw, instanced }`. [ini.js](engine/v1/core/ini.js) dropped its four template-JSON imports and now calls `InstanceEngineTemplates()`, feeding `raw` into `Blueprints`. The IIFEs and their local `toUnitVector3` copies were removed from [Model.js](engine/v1/player/Model.js) and [NewScatter.js](engine/v1/builder/NewScatter.js); both keep their JSON import and call-time reads.

**Why:** `ENGINE.Blueprints.*` (public API) was returning corrupted, post-instancing template data (radians, `Unit`/`UnitVector3` bags) to the external Simulator App, which requires the authored shape (degrees, plain `{x,y,z}`). The IIFEs mutated the shared JSON singletons at import, before `ini.js` could `structuredClone` them for the API. Capturing the raw clone at boot *before* instancing keeps the API authored while engine internals still read the instanced singletons directly (call-time). Resolves the 2026-07-21 `ENGINE.Blueprints.*` deferral. The chosen home (`builder/templates/`, a nested dir of `builder/`, same tier as `player/`) makes importing `player/characters.json` a legal same-tier import rather than an abuse of the `core/normalize.js`-only exception.

**Where:** [builder/templates/Instance.js](engine/v1/builder/templates/Instance.js) (new), [core/ini.js](engine/v1/core/ini.js), [player/Model.js](engine/v1/player/Model.js), [builder/NewScatter.js](engine/v1/builder/NewScatter.js). Rule doc [UNIT_INSTANCING.md](engine/v1/docs/rules/UNIT_INSTANCING.md) §1 gained an exception subsection for API-exposed templates. `core/normalize.js` intentionally unchanged (keeps its own `toUnitVector3` for payload normalization — engine-template vs external-payload concerns kept separate).
